section.para:
This function checks that exactly one of its arguments is non-&nil;
 and, if this is the case, returns its value and index in the argument
 list as &mul-val;, otherwise returns &nil;.

Additional &place;s:

 &funcall;
  (&setf; (&funcall; #'&symbol-r; ...)
     &object-r;) and
    (&setf; (&funcall; '&symbol-r; ...) &object-r;)
    are equivalent to (&setf; (&symbol-r; ...) &object-r;).


 &progn;
  (&setf; (&progn; &form-r; ... &place-r;)
     &object-r;)

 &locally;
  (&setf; (&locally; &declaration-r; ...
     &form-r; ... &place-r;) &object-r;)


 &if;
  (&setf; (&if; &cond-r;
     place&sub-1;
     place&sub-2;)
     &object-r;)

 &get-dispatch-macro-character;
  (&setf; (&get-dispatch-macro-character; ...)
     ...) calls &set-dispatch-macro-character;.


 &lfd;:
  (&setf; (&lfd;) &digits-r;) sets the
    default mantissa length of &long-float-t;s to &digits-r; bits.


 &values-list;
  (&setf; (&values-list; &list-r;) &form-r;)
    is equivalent to (&values-list; (&setf; &list-r;
     (&multiple-value-list; &form-r;))).
   Note that this &place; is restricted: it can only be
     used in &setf;, &letf;, &letf-star;, not in other positions.

(&special-operator-p; &symbol-r;) returns &nil; or
 &t;.  If it returns &t;, then (&symbol-function;
  &symbol-r;) returns the (useless) special operator handler.

The function
 &symbol-mex;
   SYMBOL-MACRO-EXPAND

 tests for a &symbol-macro;: If &symbol-r; is defined as a &symbol-macro;
 in the &glo-env;, (&symbol-mex; &symbol-r;) returns two
 values, &t; and the expansion; otherwise it returns &nil;.

&symbol-mex; is a special case of &macroexpand-1;. &macroexpand-1;
 can also test whether a symbol is defined as a &symbol-macro; in &lex-env;s
 other than the &glo-env;.

Calling &symbol-value; on a symbol defined as a &symbol-macro;
 returns the value of the expansion.  Calling &set; on a symbol defined
 as a &symbol-macro; calls &setf; on the expansion.

The default methods for &no-prim;, &no-applicable-method; and &no-next-method; &signal; an &error-t; of type &meth-call-err;
METHOD-CALL-ERROR . You can find out more information about the error using functions CLOS:METHOD-CALL-ERROR-GENERIC-FUNCTION, CLOS:METHOD-CALL-ERROR-ARGUMENT-LIST, and (only for &no-next-method;) CLOS:METHOD-CALL-ERROR-METHOD. Moreover, when the generic function has only one dispatching argument, (i.e., such an argument that not all the corresponding parameter specializers are &t-t;), an &error-t; of type &meth-call-type-err;
METHOD-CALL-TYPE-ERROR
is &signal;ed, additionally making &type-error-datum; and &type-error-expected-type; available.

formalpara.para:
The macro (&muffle-cerrors; {&form-r;}*)
 executes the &form-r;s; when a &cont-err; occurs whose &continue; &restart-t;
 can be invoked non-interactively (this includes all &cont-err;s signaled
 by the function &cerror;), no message is printed, instead, the &continue;
 &restart-t; is invoked.

The macro (&without-global-handlers; &body-amp;
  &body-r;) removes all global handlers, executes &body-r;, and
 then restores the handlers.

section.para:
For packages to be located in the modern
 (case-sensitive) world, you need to augment their &defpackage;
 declaration by adding the option (&modern-k; &t;).

When the package being defined already exists, it is modified as
 follows (and in this order):
  &case-sensitive-k;
   adjusted with (&setf; &pack-sensitive;)
     (with a warning)
  &case-inverted-k;
   adjusted with (&setf; &pack-inverted;)
     (with a warning)
  &modern-k;

if &cl-pac; is being used, it is un-used and
     &cs-cl; is used instead; also, &cs-cl; is used instead of &cl-pac;
     throughout the &defpackage; form, e.g.,
(&defpackage; "FOO"
  (&modern-k; &t;)
  (&use-k; "COMMON-LISP" "EXT"))
is equivalent to
(&defpackage; "FOO"
  (&case-sensitive-k; &t;)
  (&case-inverted-k; &t;)
  (&use-k; "CS-COMMON-LISP" "EXT"))

    (&modern-k; &nil;) reverts the
      effects of (&modern-k; &t;).

  :NICKNAMES
   adjusted with &rename-package;

  &documentation-k;
   reset to the new value with (&setf;
      &documentation;)
  :SHADOW
   adjusted with &shadow;

  :SHADOWING-IMPORT-FROM
   adjusted with &shadowing-import;

  &use-k;
   adjusted with &use-package; and &unuse-package;

  :IMPORT-FROM
   adjusted with &import;

  :INTERN
   adjusted with &intern; (but &not-e; &unintern;)

  :EXPORT
   adjusted with &intern; and &export; (but &not-e;
     &unexport;)
  :SIZE
   ignored

There are four floating point types: &short-float-t;, &single-float-t;, &double-float-t; and &long-float-t;:
typesignmantissa exponentcomment
&short-float-t;1 bit 16+1 bits8 bitsimmediate
&single-float-t;1 bit 23+1 bits8 bits&ieee-bfp;
&double-float-t;1 bit 52+1 bits11 bits&ieee-bfp;
&long-float-t;1 bit >=64 bits32 bitsvariable length

simplesect.para:
A similar variable, &phasecont;, controls the return
 value of &phase; when the argument is an exact nonnegative &real-t;.
 Namely, if &phasecont; is non-&nil;, it returns a floating-point zero;
 if &phasecont; is &nil;, it returns an exact zero.  Example:
 (&phase; 2/3)

