listitem.para:
If &host-r; is non-&nil; and the &directory-r;'s &startpoint-r;
 is not &absolute-k;, (&parse-namestring; (&namestring;
 &path-r;)) will not be the same as &path-r;.

A filename is split into name and type according to the
 following rule: 
  if there is no &file-dot; in the filename, then the
   &name-r; is everything, &type-r; is &nil;;
  if there is a &file-dot;, then &name-r; is the part
   before and &type-r; the part after the last dot.

if the only &file-dot; is the first character, then
   the behavior depends on the value of the user variable
    &parsedot;
   which can be either
   &type-k;
    &nil; &name-r;, everything after the &file-dot;
     is the &type-r;; or
   &name-k;
    &nil; &type-r;, everything is the
     &name-r;

Name and type may be &string-t;s of any &length;
 (consisting of &printing; &character-t;s, except &file-slash;,
 &file-bsla;, &file-colon;).

