&translate-pathname; accepts three additional keyword arguments:
 (&translate-pathname; &source-r;
 from-wildname
 to-wildname &key-amp; &all-k;
 &merge-k; &absolute-k;)

Conversely, when &pathmerge; is non-&nil;, the normal &ansi-cl;
 behavior is exhibited: (&merge-pathnames; #P"x/" #P"y/")
 evaluates to #P"y/x/".

Functions &stream-element-type; and (&setf;
 &stream-element-type;) are &generic-function-t;s, see
 .

Function &make-stream; creates a Lisp stream out of an OS &file-des;:
 (&make-stream; &object-r; &key-amp; &direction-k;
  &eltype; &extfmt; &buffered;)

&object-r; designates an OS handle (a &file-des;),
 and should be one of the following: 
  number
   denotes the &file-des; of this value

  &input-k;
   denotes &clisp; process standard input

  &output-k;
   denotes &clisp; process standard output

  &error-k;
   denotes &clisp; process standard error

  &stream-t;
   denotes the handle of this stream, which should be
     a &file-stream-t; or a &socket-stream;

